# Changelog

All notable changes to this project are documented in this file.

## 3.0.2 - 2026-06-05

Scheduler-only release. The SQL schema is unchanged from 3.0.1;
`ALTER EXTENSION pg_dbms_job UPDATE TO '3.0.2';` only advances the version.
Restart the scheduler binary to pick up the fix.

### Fixed
- Bounded the daemon's memory use under heavy asynchronous-job load, where RSS
  grew with the number of in-flight jobs and was only released once the backlog
  drained. Three buffers that scaled with load are now capped:
  - Worker concurrency is limited to the effective connection-pool size
    (`min(job_queue_processes, pool_size)`) instead of `job_queue_processes`.
    Previously a burst could spawn up to `job_queue_processes` (default 1024)
    threads, most of them blocked waiting on the much smaller pool while each
    held a thread stack.
  - Worker threads now use a 512 KiB stack instead of the 2 MiB default, since
    they only drive SQL over a pooled connection.
  - The log writer's channel is now bounded, so a logging burst (especially
    debug logging under load) applies backpressure to producers instead of
    buffering an unbounded queue of pending lines. No log lines are dropped and
    timestamps remain accurate (lines are stamped at event time before
    queueing).
- Lowered the pooled-connection checkout timeout from r2d2's 30 s default to
  10 s so a momentarily saturated pool can't pin a worker (and its stack) for
  half a minute. A thread that still fails to spawn leaves the job's dispatch
  marker set, so the stale-job reaper re-queues it instead of losing work.
- Made the "worker pool full" backpressure cheap and quiet now that it is
  reached routinely (the cap equals the pool size rather than the old 1024).
  The dispatcher polls for a free slot on a short fixed interval instead of
  sleeping a full `error_delay` each time — the coarse wait would otherwise
  throttle drain throughput to roughly `pool_size` jobs per `error_delay`. The
  saturation notice is now emitted at LOG level and rate-limited to once per
  `error_delay` seconds (shared across both dispatch loops) rather than once per
  poll, so a sustained backlog no longer floods the log.

### Changed
- Logging no longer holds the global logger lock across the (now bounded,
  possibly blocking) channel send. The sender is cloned out under the lock and
  the send happens lock-free, so a backed-up log writer can't stall other
  threads' logging — including the main dispatch loop — behind one producer.

### Added
- Unit tests for the worker-concurrency cap (`effective_max_workers`), the
  worker-slot backpressure wait (`await_worker_slot`: immediate return below the
  cap, reaping finished workers, and blocking-then-logging when saturated), the
  bounded log channel draining a high-volume burst without loss, and
  compile-time sanity bounds on the new tuning constants.

## 3.0.1 - 2026-06-01

Scheduler-only release. The SQL schema is unchanged from 3.0.0;
`ALTER EXTENSION pg_dbms_job UPDATE TO '3.0.1';` only advances the version.
Restart the scheduler binary to pick up the fix.

### Fixed
- Lowered submit-to-execution latency. Each dispatch cycle used to wait an
  extra full `nap_time` even after a job's notification had already arrived,
  because the postgres `TimeoutIter` resets its delay on every notification and
  only returns once it has seen a full `nap_time` of silence. The main loop now
  blocks at most once per cycle for the first notification, then drains any
  others without blocking, so a submitted job dispatches in milliseconds instead
  of up to one `nap_time` (and never two).

### Added
- Unit tests around the notification-collection logic (`collect_notifications`)
  guaranteeing the loop blocks at most once per dispatch cycle and that a cycle
  never costs two `nap_time`s.

## 3.0.0 - 2026-05-29

First release of the Rust-based line. The scheduler and the SQL extension now
share a single version (3.0.0); the historical `-rust` suffix on the scheduler
has been dropped.

### Removed
- The legacy Perl scheduler (`bin/pg_dbms_job`) and its Perl TAP test suite
  (`t/`, `test/`). The scheduler is now Rust-only; its tests run with
  `cargo test` in `rust/`.

### Added
- Configurable job-history recording via `job_run_details` (`all` | `errors` |
  `none`, default `all`) to bound the growth of
  `dbms_job.all_scheduler_job_run_details`.
- `stale_job_timeout` (seconds, default `3600`, `0` disables): a reaper that
  re-queues jobs left flagged running (`this_date` set) by a worker that never
  finished. It only acts on jobs older than the timeout with no live worker
  backend in `pg_stat_activity`, so a long-running job is never re-queued while
  still executing.
- Monthly range-partitioning of `dbms_job.all_scheduler_job_run_details` (for
  fresh installs), with a DEFAULT catch-all partition and the
  `dbms_job.maintain_run_details_partitions(months_ahead, retention_months)`
  maintenance function for creating upcoming partitions and dropping old ones.
- Standalone migration script
  `updates/migrate_all_scheduler_job_run_details_to_partitioned.sql` to convert
  an existing history table to partitioned.
- Partial dispatch indexes (`all_async_jobs_pending_idx`,
  `all_scheduled_jobs_pending_idx`) and aggressive per-table autovacuum settings
  on the queue tables, shipped with the extension.
- `Makefile` targets that build and install the Rust scheduler binary
  (`rust-build`, `rust-install`, `rust-clean`); `make` / `make install` now
  build and install the daemon alongside the SQL extension.

### Changed
- Unified scheduler + SQL extension version at 3.0.0; dropped the `-rust`
  scheduler version suffix.
- Documentation (root `README.md`, `rust/README.md`) updated to be Rust-only and
  to document the current configuration options, defaults, and the
  partitioning/retention model.

### Upgrade notes
- `ALTER EXTENSION pg_dbms_job UPDATE TO '3.0.0';` adds the indexes, autovacuum
  settings, and the partition-maintenance function. Converting the existing
  history table to partitioned is a separate, deliberate step — run
  `updates/migrate_all_scheduler_job_run_details_to_partitioned.sql` by hand.
- Review the scheduler config: size `pool_size` to what the database can serve
  well (roughly CPU cores x 2-4) and keep `job_queue_processes` <= `pool_size`.
